  <span id="freeText12095511168339235148" style="display:none">The beginning and the end of this novel are superb. Le Carre at his best, mixing a thriller plot with humor and biting social criticism. The middle is a confusing mess of African characters, causes, and conspiracies‚Äîit‚Äôs hard to follow and sometimes tedious. <br />Le Carre creates a marvelous character, Bruno Salvador (‚ÄúSalvo‚Äù) who‚Äôs the son of an bog Irish priest who served his whole life in the Congo and a Congolese woman who was sent back to her village after the birth. After his father‚Äôs death, by a fluke Salvo is declared a British citizen and sent to a Catholic school in Surrey were he was raised by Brother Michael, who uses him sexually but sees to his education using funds from his own rich Catholic family. His dying gift, Aunt Imelda‚Äôs watch, plays a significant role in the novel. <br />As the book begins, the na√Øve but likable Salvo (who narrates his own story) is a top notch translator, speaking not only English, French and Swahili, but most of the dialects of the Congo as well. He‚Äôs much in demand in London where he‚Äôs married to socialite Penelope, rising newspaper star who married him to peak her father. It‚Äôs clear she‚Äôs regretting her decision and Salvo doesn‚Äôt seem too heart broken though he moves heaven and earth to be on time to a do at the paper honoring an award she‚Äôs received. He has to leave the Congolese nurse, Hannah, he‚Äôs just met and fallen in love with, though, on a job to translate for a dying man in a North London hospital. Arriving at the party, he‚Äôs whisked off by his British government employer with an extra special job for him‚Äîone for which he has to sign the Official Secrets Act.<br /></span>
